# Azure DevOps vs Polarion Boundary

## Azure DevOps (execution layer)

Use for: Features, User Stories, Tasks, Bugs, iterations, capacity, PI Objectives, dependencies, backlog queries, sprint assignment, comments, PR links, wiki process docs.

MCP server: `azure-devops` (domains: core, wiki, work, work-items)

## Polarion (specification & compliance layer)

Use for: formal requirements, SRS/LiveDocs, requirement reviews and approvals, requirement-to-implementation links, test result records on Polarion test runs, configuration SRS inventory.

MCP server: `polarion-mcp`

## Linking, not duplicating

- A User Story in ADO may **implement** or **trace to** a Polarion requirement — link them; do not copy full spec text into ADO unless summarizing for sprint context
- Acceptance criteria in ADO should be **testable sprint commitments**; Polarion holds authoritative requirement language
- Status changes: update the system where the item lives; sync both only when the user's workflow requires it

## Before creating work items

Ask (or infer from context): Is this execution tracking (ADO) or formal specification (Polarion)? When unclear, default to ADO for Stories/Tasks and Polarion for requirements-level artifacts.
